WHAT'S UP (there)?

This tutorial for CMSC320 will be exploring a dataset of over 80,000 UFO sightings over the past century. I will be using the scrubbed dataset provided on Kaggle. You can find it with the following link: https://www.kaggle.com/NUFORC/ufo-sightings?select=scrubbed.csv.

The overall motivation behind this tutorial is to find trends in UFO sightings. Are certain areas of the country "hotspots"? How long do sightings normally last? What kinds of 'shapes' do people see when they do report a sighting? Have there been any significant clusters of sightings in the past that indicate something unknown really may have been out there? All questions we can try and answer...

Eva Utzschneider

In [4]:
# If we look at our .info again, we'll see that it reduced our total number of entries by almost 15,000. However, we 
# still have a couple more housekeeping things to take care of before we can really get into the data exploration part
# of this tutorial. You'll notice in the .info that the types of most of the columns are objects, but to have an easier
# time comparing and measuring them later, we will want them in suitable formats. 

# Adding two new columns for separate date and time values (will need to handle the 24:00 for some of the entries).
df[['date','time']] = df.datetime.str.split(expand=True)

# Changing 24:00 entries to 23:59 so they fit within the datetime constraints of Pandas. 
df.loc[df.time == '24:00', 'time'] = '23:59'

# Deleting the old datetime column (with 24:00 values)
df.drop('datetime', axis=1)

# Replacing the old datetime column with new one that has every time between 00:00 and 23:59, as pandas likes, and then
# converting that to datetime format. 
df['datetime'] = df['date'] + ' ' + df['time']
df['datetime'] = pd.to_datetime(df['datetime'], dayfirst=True)

# Now the only columns left for us to reformat are duration (in seconds) and the latitude values (longitude are already floats). 
df['duration (seconds)'] = pd.to_numeric(df['duration (seconds)'], errors = 'coerce')
df['latitude'] = df.latitude.astype(float)

EXPLORATORY DATA ANALYSIS

There are a lot of cool relationships we can investigate with this dataset. We'll start off with more straightforward, general ones and then get into summary statistics that can hopefully lead us to some linear regressions to test.

In [6]:
# Number of reported sightings every year. 

print(df.datetime.min())
print(df.datetime.max())

# Slicing the data to only include data after 1914 (since the last recorded entry is 2014, I think having an even 
# 100 years will make for better grouping later on).
df_sum = df[df['datetime'] >= '1914-01-01']
df_sum['year'] = df['datetime'].dt.year

df_counts = df_sum.groupby(['year']).size().reset_index(name='counts')
ax_counts = df_counts.plot.scatter(x='year', y='counts', title='UFO Sightings Over Time')

1910-01-01 23:59:00
2014-12-04 22:23:00

Based on the scatterplot, we can see that in the mid-to-late 90's a spike in recorded UFO appearences was experienced in the U.S. Maybe it had something to do with the release of E.T. in 1982? Anyways, we'll investigate further and see if we can uncover anymore localized trends that occurred during this spike.

# There are a total of 837 sightings in Maryland, which makes for a good number of locations to plot. Overall, this kind
# of data is perfect for a map because the sightings are location-oriented and you have different identifiers that could
# be used to differentiate points (like shape of the UFO and duration). 

# To get our map started we need to first make sure that Folium will load its map looking at the area of interest, 
# in this case, Maryland. 
# For any location, you can Google the coordinates, and then play with the zoom_start until you feel like the entire 
# area is in the lens of the map. From there, you can also toggle the coordinates a bit to maximize the space. 

map_osm = folium.Map(location=[39.03, -76.94], zoom_start=7.5)

df_md['shape'].unique().tolist()

In [32]:
df_md.reset_index()

for i in range(0, len(df_md)):
    # Round shapes will be blue
    if df_md.iloc[i]['shape'] == ('sphere' or 'cylinder' or 'oval' or 'circle' or 'egg' or 'teardrop' or 'disk'):
        folium.Marker(
            location=[df_md.iloc[i]['latitude'], df_md.iloc[i]['longitude']],
            popup=df_md.iloc[i]['comments'],
        ).add_to(map_osm)
    
    # "Light" shapes will be green
    elif df_md.iloc[i]['shape'] == ('light' or 'flash'):
        folium.Marker(
            location = [df_md.iloc[i]['latitude'], df_md.iloc[i]['longitude']],
            popup=df_md.iloc[i]['comments'],
            icon = folium.Icon(color='green'),
            ).add_to(map_osm)
        
    # Rectangular shapes will be red
    elif df_md.iloc[i]['shape'] == ('rectangle' or 'diamond'):
        folium.Marker(
            location = [df_md.iloc[i]['latitude'], df_md.iloc[i]['longitude']],
            popup=df_md.iloc[i]['comments'],
            icon = folium.Icon(color='red'),
            ).add_to(map_osm)
        
    # Triangular shapes will be yellow
    elif df_md.iloc[i]['shape'] == ('triangle' or 'chevron'):
        folium.Marker(
            location = [df_md.iloc[i]['latitude'], df_md.iloc[i]['longitude']],
            popup=df_md.iloc[i]['comments'],
            icon = folium.Icon(color='yellow'),
            ).add_to(map_osm)
    else:
        folium.Marker(
            location = [df_md.iloc[i]['latitude'], df_md.iloc[i]['longitude']],
            popup=df_md.iloc[i]['comments'],
            icon = folium.Icon(color='brown'),
            ).add_to(map_osm)
        
map_osm

The map gives us some pretty interesting insights. I would have imagined that most of the sightings would have been in Western Maryland where the area is more rural. Albeit with less people living there less people to report sightings. It seems the most common descriptors for sightings in Maryland have been some variation of 'round' or a 'flash of light,' which also makes sense considering UFOS far away probably can't give off very distinct shapes.
